		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Unrest - A guide to pulling from the manor</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:rjgood@mindspring.com">Rotep</a> | 
		            1/8/2001 7:22:29 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Hail all undead slayers of Norrath! This guide focuses on the Estate of Unrest, a Dwarven noble's manor that has long since been taken over my filthy undead creatures. Actually, I hear that the Dwarven noble has been resurrected as a very unhappy ghost, although I have not seen him yet.<BR>
<BR>
This guide was scribed to help those from low 20s to mid 20s pull from Unrest Manor to the walls outside of the manor. This guide is not for those who want to learn about camping specific rooms in Unrest, for other notable storytellers have covered that subject well.<BR>
<BR>
It is my hopes that this guide helps my fellow undead slayers with their quest into Unrest Manor.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Finding a place to call home...<BR>
It is important to have a good location in which to fight. For this guide, there are only two places...left wall (West wall) and the back wall (South wall.) The two walls are out of the way of trains pulled from the manor.<BR>
<BR>
Also, it is important to be against the wall straight out from the back door or the side door (only 1 side door on left/west side.) This allows the puller to pull straight out the door and get the creature to the group as quickly as possible.<BR>
<BR>
My personal preference is the back wall straight out from the back door (south wall, middle of wall.) Why? Because the back door has access to a round room of low 20 creatures, *and* the back door is near the back staircase where harder creatures can be pulled from the 2nd floor.<BR>
<BR>
Note: The yard creatures will only agro on hunters that are lower than 22 seasons. Remember this when pulling and meditating...death beetles, tormented dead and greater skeletons will join the fight if you have hunters younger than 22 seasons. Be prepared to take on more than your pull.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Finding an undead creature to send back to the dead...<BR>
Now that ye have a place to fight and meditate, it is time to search the manor for creatures that are good to destroy.<BR>
<BR>
First, walk through the door closest to your group (or battle spot if you are solo) and fan out looking for &#8216;blue&#8217; creatures. This will require a paladin and cleric incantation of Invisibility Against Undead. Full invisibility does not work against the undead, since the undead can sense straight through the Invisibility spell.<BR>
<BR>
Note: For those in early 20s, the 1st floor has some decent creatures to kill. Those in early 20s need only to pull from the 1st floor. Those hunters in their mid 20s must pull from the 2nd floor and the Basement for good creatures to slay.<BR>
<BR>
Preparing the way for the formidable creatures...<BR>
By this point, you have a place to pull to, and you have found some good &#8216;blue&#8217; creatures that are fairly close to the back or side door.<BR>
<BR>
This next step will bore even the most veteran of groups...killing meaningless &#8216;green&#8217; creatures. Your goal here is to backtrack to the first creature that you see when walking into the door from the pull spot. I know, my friend, this fetid creature is green. Have your druid or ranger cast harmony on all surrounding &#8216;green&#8217; creatures and pull the one closest to the door.<BR>
<BR>
After you slay the creature closest to the door, go back in and slay the 2nd closest creature to the door. Do this until ALL low-level creatures between the door and your &#8216;blue&#8217; pulls are dead. This is a *must* for any puller younger than 28th season. If you do not kill all of those easy creatures in your path to the door, they will all come when you pull your formidable creature.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Pulling the formidable creatures...<BR>
You have cleared all easier creatures out of the way, but double check to make sure. The last thing that we want is unwanted additions during your pull. Invisible to the undead, make your way back to the creatures that you decided to pull in the first place. Check the area again for any new additions to the undead party.<BR>
<BR>
If the undead creature is alone, or with one other creature...pull down the path that you came, out the door and to the group. If there are more than 2 creatures in sight, do not pull unless your group can take all in sight *plus* any additional creatures from hallway closets.<BR>
<BR>
But for the rest of us undead slayers, we prefer to be more cautious for our first &#8216;hard&#8217; pull. Have your caster of the harmony incantation (druid or ranger) stand on your cleared path, so that they do not need Invisibility Versus Undead. You are invisible to the undead, so you run right up to the extra creatures that you do not want to come with the pull. Have the harmony caster harmony *on you* from his/her &#8216;safe spot.&#8217; Since harmony is an Area Effect spell, all creatures around you will be non-aggressive.<BR>
<BR>
Now go to your creature, and hit him as hard as you can. Being undead and brainless, the creature will begin attacking you.<BR>
<BR>
Run down your path and out the door, pulling the creature straight to the group.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
What did you just say?<BR>
Once the creature is dead, start all over and:<BR>
1. Clear out the &#8216;greens&#8217; in your pulling path.<BR>
2. Hamony any extra &#8216;blues&#8217; around the one that you want to pull.<BR>
3. Pull the blue that you want.<BR>
<BR>
Pulling in Unrest is a simple as that (ROFLMAO.) Aye, this does seem to be long and drawn out just to pull a &#8216;blue&#8217; creature. But, once you start this cycle, the blues can be pulled constantly and controlled...one, two or three at a time for your entire hunting day.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Pulling from the 2nd Floor lobby...<BR>
Mid 20s hunters &#8211; The basement and 2nd floor is where you will have to pull from. Very few blue creatures on 1st Level.<BR>
<BR>
Camp at the back wall and pull through the back door. The back door is very close to the back staircase, which leads to the 2nd floor. The lobby in the 2nd floor has 4 or 5 low 20s (blue) creatures standing right at the top of the stairs on the 2nd floor. This makes pulling blues easy, especially if you can harmony those on *both* sides of the one closest to the staircase. Remember to harmony all sides around the creature (2 or 3 harmony casts.) If you don&#8217;t, the ones in the 2nd floor closets will join the fight.<BR>
<BR>
And watch out for the room on the right of the back staircase on the 2nd Floor. This is called the Magi room, and it contains 4 creatures when full. You might have to harmony those nearest the door/stairs before pulling from the 2nd floor lobby. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
One more thing, &#8216;pathing&#8217; when you pull...<BR>
Creatures will get lost easily! This is the undead that we are talking about here...they are brainless and a disease on the living. Do not expect them to follow your speed and acrobatics.<BR>
<BR>
When pulling, follow the shortest and most simple path. Do not jump over rails or obstacles. The unrest creatures *will* lose you and start collecting their friends to join the fight.<BR>
<BR>
Do not run anywhere besides right down your &#8216;pull path.&#8217; You will drag additions with your pull if you walk by a creature.<BR>
<BR>
Pull slowly and deliberately the first couple of times until you know that your &#8216;pull path&#8217; is safe. It is ok to let them beat you up a little bit...at least you know they are on you and not walking around collecting friends. Once your path is safe, you can start running full speed while pulling to your group.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Things to know about Estate of Unrest...<BR>
<BR>
* Safe places in Unrest: Against the side walls and back walls. Some inside camps are safe.  Very few front-yard locations are safe...avoid the front.<BR>
<BR>
* Unsafe places in Unrest: Stay away from the zone! Stay away from the fountains! Trains are pulled by hunters of every level and of every class. In my 26th season, a 40th season hunter trained 3 of the deadliest undead all around the yard and to the zone. Those in the yard were safe, since the 40th hunter still had them on him. Once the 40th season zoned, all near the zone were wiped out in seconds. All near the front door were wiped out. You get the picture....the yard folks lived.<BR>
<BR>
* Do not camp the inside rooms near the doors: This is where people pull the trains out to the zone, and this is where the trains pass by when they return. Plus, other hunter&#8217;s pulls will join in your fights...and their pulls may be a lot harder than yours.<BR>
<BR>
* Hunting parties are hard to find sometimes. Soloing or partnering? No problem...just follow the 3 steps and start pulling 1 blue at a time. Will take longer, but at least you are active, getting kills and loot. This will buy you time and get you warmed up for more members to join.<BR>
<BR>
* There is decent loot on all first floor creatures. Even solo, a mid 20s hunter can collect quite a stack of platinum from pulling &#8216;green&#8217; creatures from the first floor. Even yard creatures will drop bronze and platinum.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Thank you for listening to my feeble storytelling. This is information that I would have found useful upon arriving at the Estate of Unrest. Good luck to you, slayer of the undead!<BR>
<BR>
Rotep<BR>
Human Paladin<BR>
Loyal servant of Mithaniel Marr
